title: Senior Intelligence Officer
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed intelligence support for programs and activities at Hill AFB, including the F-16 fighter, Minuteman ICBM, Ground Theater Air Control System, Range Threat Systems, and various USAF precision-guided munitions. Supervised 1 officer, 1 enlisted and, GS-13s and 2 GS-12s. Produced assessments, briefings, and intelligence bulletins in support of program vulnerability assessment and countermeasure development. Coordinated program intelligence production requirements and provided advice on intelligence policy and issues. Provided Geospacial Information and Services (GI&S) and coordinate program GI&S requirements. Provided current situation briefings to base senior leaders and staffs, and intelligence support for force protection, OPSEC, and information assurance efforts. Provided oversight of Hill AFB’s Sensitive Information (SCI) security program, consisting of 5 SCI facilities, approximately 900 billets, a TOP SECRET local area network, and 6 SCI contracts.

title: Acquisition Product Manager, F/A-18 Combat ID
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed software development of the F/A-18 fighter’s Positive Identification System (PIDS)—a $5.2M/yr. effort. Included software for multiple identification subsystems, F/A-18 operational flight programs, and their interfaces with the Tactical Mission Planning System (TAMPS). Planned, scheduled and budgeted government and contractor software development and testing. Provided technical inputs to Operational Requirements Documents (ORD’s), contracts, the Test and Evaluation Master Plan, and classification guides. Translated broad operational requirements into system-level functional requirements. Ensured government and contractor software development proceeded on schedule in accordance with approved quality and testing standards. Coordinated aircraft modifications required for avionics flight tests, and ensured safety of flight requirements were met. Performed laboratory and flight tests on system hardware and software; analyzed data to identify avionics and pilot/vehicle interface problems; and implemented feasible and cost-effective technical solutions.

title: Facility Program Manager
name: Rick Bolin
description: Headed Situation Awareness Technology Office, providing engineering and flight test support for two tactical avionics advanced technology demonstration programs. In FY95, this was a 4.5 man‑year, $1.2M effort. Functionally supervised six GS‑13's matrixed from other organizations. Provided program sponsor with technical advice on operational requirements, program plans, optimal system design, threat considerations, pilot‑to‑vehicle interface, and multi‑sensor integration. Assisted with statement of work development and provided technical oversight for $5.5M contracted effort. Provided oversight of program security at China Lake. Developed operational security plans and ensured they were properly implemented. Conducted safety of flight and aircraft integration tests on avionics hardware and software. Obtained flight clearance for one‑of‑a‑kind experimental aircraft stores. Planned, coordinated, and provided logistic support for flight tests on USN and USAF test ranges. Produced written reports and multimedia presentations to document program results. Served as Navy representative to the F‑22 Threat Working Group. Helped transition successful demonstration project to production.

title: Threat Specialist
name: Rick Bolin
description: Provided threat and analytical support for concept evaluation of advanced tactical aircraft including the F‑22, AFX, F/A‑18 E/F, A‑12 and NATF. Authored white papers on threat priorities. Assisted with requirement definition, defining statements of work, and monitoring contracts. Managed threat support for contractor survivability and vulnerability analysis. Led technical review of multi‑million $ contractor survivability/vulnerability analysis for A‑12. Developed scenarios and assisted with government mission effectiveness analysis using many‑versus‑many models. Served as RED player for man‑in‑the‑loop simulations. Produced briefings and written reports on analysis results. Identified overlooked threat drivers on numerous occasions, resulting in concept design improvements. Generated test plans for experimental equipment being evaluated on Navy and USAF ranges. Served as test director during flight tests. Supported tactics development for low‑observable aircraft.

title: Air Defense Tactics Division Head
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed the Air Defense Tactics Division of SPEAR, a department responsible for producing intelligence on Russian and 3rd World air defense capabilities. Supervised two GS‑12 and two 0‑3 analysts. Served as command expert on Soviet‑style integrated air defense system (IADS) operation, AWACS employment, and air defense command and control (C3). Produced comprehensive studies on air defense capabilities of selected countries. Represented Navy at Joint Tactics Analysis Team meetings and conferences. Conducted theater‑oriented threat seminars for deploying Carrier Battle Groups. Presented annual threat seminars to approximately 70 Navy and Marine Corps TACAIR squadrons worldwide. Directed team that performed post‑analysis of USN-Libyan fighter engagement of 4 JAN 1989. Provided adhoc intelligence support to TOPGUN, MAWTS, STRIKE U and other tactical training commands. Acted as Navy technical review authority for MCM 3‑1, the primary anti‑air threat reference and counter-tactics guide for the armed services. Attained highest possible ratings on performance evaluations and received "Superior Civilian Service" award.

title: Tactical Command and Control Analyst
name: Rick Bolin
description: Helped stand up SPEAR, a new organization comprised of intelligence analysts and naval aviators designed to improve the quality of intelligence reaching operating forces. Analyzed all‑source intelligence and provided threat information to operating forces. Authored or co-authored 7 studies focused on air defense capabilities. Provided 22 briefings at up to 3‑Star level. Headed a USN/USMC working group that helped author MCM 3‑1, the primary air threat reference and counter-tactics guide for the armed services. Represented the Navy on the Joint Service Proforma Coordinating Group, the WSSIC 3rd World C3 Subpanel, the European SAM Tactics Analysis Team, and the JSTPS Enemy Attrition Advisory Group. Contributed to System Threat Assessment Reports produced by Naval Technical Intelligence Center. Headed the Navy delegation to a new foreign intelligence exchange program. Authored portions of National Intelligence Estimates and fleet Operational Tactics Guides. Identified intelligence gaps and generated collection requirements and guidelines for HUMINT, ELINT and SIGINT collection systems. Rated "Outstanding" on all performance evaluations.

title: Senior Staff
name: Rick Bolin
description: Provided engineering and technical support for the US Navy. Reviewed and provided inputs to 67 changes to Trident and SSN‑688 Class electronic system manuals. Work commended by NAVSEA for significantly improving manuals’ accuracy and usefulness. Authored new chapter describing a complex special purpose passive sonar system. Determined the requirements for protecting special hull coatings and side‑mounted sonar arrays on SSN‑688 Class submarines, and authored the applicable operating procedures. Developed technical manuals for the AN/BSY‑1 Combat System on the Seawolf class attack submarine. Performed a complete quality review of the cabling and circuit diagrams for a major AN/BSY‑1 (SUBACS) combat system unit. Assisted with proposal development.

title: Joint Intelligence Research Office (JIRO) Analyst
name: Rick Bolin
description: Served as the JIRO representative on the Technical Support Group, an intelligence advisory cell that evaluated the most sensitive intelligence available for future threat impacts on US systems, and made technical, policy, and funding recommendations for countermeasures to a Navy Flag Officer panel. Analyzed unique information on Soviet tactical C3 and electronic warfare systems, and provided the panel with reports, position papers or briefings on items of significance. Co-authored a major threat assessment titled "Soviet Air Defense Data Links”. Identified major deficiencies in tactical air defense C3 countermeasures, resulting in the formation of a Flag Officer chaired working group tasked to recommend and prioritize programmatic responses. Recommended system capability changes that were adopted for the Battle Group Passive Horizon Extension System (BGPHES), the ALQ‑149/99 jammers, and two classified intelligence systems. Generated a comprehensive intelligence collection requirements and guidance package adopted as high priority tasking for Navy and national collection assets. Represented the Office of Naval Warfare (OP‑95) on the Joint Service Proforma Coordinating Group, a SECDEF mandated Weapon System Commonality Committee, and a Navy Electronic Warfare Working Group. Maintained databases, coordinated meetings, and prepared Flag Officer correspondence.

title: Submarine Weapons and Sensors Analyst
name: Rick Bolin
description: Senior Analyst of Submarine Systems Division. Analyzed all‑source scientific and technical intelligence on foreign submarines. Provided 26 in‑depth briefings on foreign submarine developments to audiences up to Deputy SECDEF level. Contributed regularly to 6 different types of intelligence publications. Authored study presented as a Navy position paper at a multi‑national Maritime Intelligence Conference. Produced the first comprehensive analysis of the Soviet 3rd generation nuclear submarine threat which was published as the lead article in the Naval Scientific and Technical Intelligence Review, and was used by the Director of Naval Intelligence in reporting to Congress. Generated intelligence collection requirements and provided feedback to collectors. Maintained databases on submarine characteristics. Acting Division Head during incumbent's absences, supervising five Naval Officers and two GS‑6. Rated on performance evaluation as the #1 Lieutenant out of 15 at the command.

title: Quality Assurance Officer
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed the quality assurance (QA) program of a 1000‑man ship that provided repair and logistic services to a squadron of 6 nuclear submarines. Ensured repair standards were met for all non‑nuclear systems. Supervised 26 senior enlisted. Managed training and qualifications program for welders, brazers, and QA inspectors. Reviewed and approved plans and certification testing for over 280 controlled repairs, achieving a zero rate of recurring failures. COMSUBPAC inspection of QA program stated "...the program was excellent...well managed and expertly supervised.” Served as senior officer onboard after working hours, responsible for casualty team training and response, logistic services for submarines (mooring, power, etc.), engineering plant operations, and nuclear weapons security. Completed a Nuclear Regulatory Commission audit of the radiography facility with no significant discrepancies. Received Navy Commendation Medal for "...superb performance...”.

title: Senior Chief Sonar Technician
name: Rick Bolin
description: Lead sonar specialist onboard a Sturgeon‑class fast attack submarine assigned to Submarine Development Squadron Twelve. Supervised 14 sonar technicians in the operation and maintenance of a $40M complex of active and passive sonars and associated digital processing equipment. Developed sonar search plans and made ASW‑related tactical recommendations. Tested and evaluated experimental equipment. Supervised acoustic intelligence (ACINT) collection. Supervised and trained sonar operators in acoustic signature analysis and equipment operation. Trained ship's officers and sonar specialists on Soviet submarine, surface ship, and weapon systems characteristics. Monitored and analyzed ship's radiated noise. Selected for direct commissioning as a US Naval Officer.

description: Handpicked by the Major General Recruiting Mission Commander and Lieutenant General Senior Army Accessions Commander and led a diverse 586 member multi-function staff (Military, Civilian and Contract) in support of manning, training, and sustaining over 13,500 Soldiers, Civilians and Contractors, 1600 facilities, 10,000 vehicles, and an annual budget exceeding 308 million dollars to accomplish the Army’s recruiting mission in the United States, its territories, and overseas locations. Responsible for the successful day to day operations of the command and directly managed the commands personnel actions, operations, public affairs, budget planning and execution, personnel professional development programs, and synchronization of all staff efforts to meet the commands priorities and accomplishment goals. • Led the command’s efforts in supervising / managing civilian and military career development and ensured the command’s personnel were trained and ready to execute operations within the current doctrine, tactics, techniques and procedures and adhered to published guidelines and regulations. • Led a comprehensive review/modernization of all business practices resulting in a record breaking year of success; best results in the 37 year history of the All-Recruited All-Volunteer Force. • Led the commands detailed analysis of world-wide environmental conditions, cultural nuances, socio-economic analysis, emerging trends, current characteristics, and developed viable actions plans to meet mission requirements. • Maintained close liaison with National Government agencies as well as local, county, and state agencies to maximize cooperation and to meet mission requirements. • Coordinated the efforts of multiple cross functional and geographically dispersed teams in challenging environments to exceed production objectives.

The board’s members were influential leaders in business, education, government, professional sports and entertainment industries. The advisory boards were adopted command wide as a best practice. • Led the brigade’s efforts in supervising / managing civilian and military career development and ensured the command’s personnel were trained and ready to execute recruiting operations within the current doctrine, tactics, techniques and procedures and adhered to published guidelines and regulations. • Provided adaptive leadership, organizational effectiveness, team building, and professional development to produce desired results. • Created and produced a detailed recruiting systems analysis guide that included local and regional underlying economic conditions and characteristics, emerging trends, best operations methods, and methods to maximize local support from individual and group centers of influence.

description: 2003-2005 Battalion Commander, United States Army Recruiting Command, Dallas, Texas 2001-2003 Senior Intelligence Officer - G2, 7th INFANTRY Division, Fort Carson, Colorado 2000-2001 Chief of Intelligence Plans, III Corps, Fort Hood, Texas 1999-2000 Executive Officer, 104th Military Intelligence Battalion, Fort Hood, Texas 1998-1999 Operational Planner, 4th INFANTRY Division, Fort Hood, Texas

title: Senior Intelligence Officer
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed intelligence support for programs and activities at Hill AFB, including the F-16 fighter, Minuteman ICBM, Ground Theater Air Control System, Range Threat Systems, and various USAF precision-guided munitions. Supervised 1 officer, 1 enlisted and, GS-13s and 2 GS-12s. Produced assessments, briefings, and intelligence bulletins in support of program vulnerability assessment and countermeasure development. Coordinated program intelligence production requirements and provided advice on intelligence policy and issues. Provided Geospacial Information and Services (GI&S) and coordinate program GI&S requirements. Provided current situation briefings to base senior leaders and staffs, and intelligence support for force protection, OPSEC, and information assurance efforts. Provided oversight of Hill AFB’s Sensitive Information (SCI) security program, consisting of 5 SCI facilities, approximately 900 billets, a TOP SECRET local area network, and 6 SCI contracts.

title: Acquisition Product Manager, F/A-18 Combat ID
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed software development of the F/A-18 fighter’s Positive Identification System (PIDS)—a $5.2M/yr. effort. Included software for multiple identification subsystems, F/A-18 operational flight programs, and their interfaces with the Tactical Mission Planning System (TAMPS). Planned, scheduled and budgeted government and contractor software development and testing. Provided technical inputs to Operational Requirements Documents (ORD’s), contracts, the Test and Evaluation Master Plan, and classification guides. Translated broad operational requirements into system-level functional requirements. Ensured government and contractor software development proceeded on schedule in accordance with approved quality and testing standards. Coordinated aircraft modifications required for avionics flight tests, and ensured safety of flight requirements were met. Performed laboratory and flight tests on system hardware and software; analyzed data to identify avionics and pilot/vehicle interface problems; and implemented feasible and cost-effective technical solutions.

title: Facility Program Manager
name: Rick Bolin
description: Headed Situation Awareness Technology Office, providing engineering and flight test support for two tactical avionics advanced technology demonstration programs. In FY95, this was a 4.5 man‑year, $1.2M effort. Functionally supervised six GS‑13's matrixed from other organizations. Provided program sponsor with technical advice on operational requirements, program plans, optimal system design, threat considerations, pilot‑to‑vehicle interface, and multi‑sensor integration. Assisted with statement of work development and provided technical oversight for $5.5M contracted effort. Provided oversight of program security at China Lake. Developed operational security plans and ensured they were properly implemented. Conducted safety of flight and aircraft integration tests on avionics hardware and software. Obtained flight clearance for one‑of‑a‑kind experimental aircraft stores. Planned, coordinated, and provided logistic support for flight tests on USN and USAF test ranges. Produced written reports and multimedia presentations to document program results. Served as Navy representative to the F‑22 Threat Working Group. Helped transition successful demonstration project to production.

title: Threat Specialist
name: Rick Bolin
description: Provided threat and analytical support for concept evaluation of advanced tactical aircraft including the F‑22, AFX, F/A‑18 E/F, A‑12 and NATF. Authored white papers on threat priorities. Assisted with requirement definition, defining statements of work, and monitoring contracts. Managed threat support for contractor survivability and vulnerability analysis. Led technical review of multi‑million $ contractor survivability/vulnerability analysis for A‑12. Developed scenarios and assisted with government mission effectiveness analysis using many‑versus‑many models. Served as RED player for man‑in‑the‑loop simulations. Produced briefings and written reports on analysis results. Identified overlooked threat drivers on numerous occasions, resulting in concept design improvements. Generated test plans for experimental equipment being evaluated on Navy and USAF ranges. Served as test director during flight tests. Supported tactics development for low‑observable aircraft.

title: Air Defense Tactics Division Head
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed the Air Defense Tactics Division of SPEAR, a department responsible for producing intelligence on Russian and 3rd World air defense capabilities. Supervised two GS‑12 and two 0‑3 analysts. Served as command expert on Soviet‑style integrated air defense system (IADS) operation, AWACS employment, and air defense command and control (C3). Produced comprehensive studies on air defense capabilities of selected countries. Represented Navy at Joint Tactics Analysis Team meetings and conferences. Conducted theater‑oriented threat seminars for deploying Carrier Battle Groups. Presented annual threat seminars to approximately 70 Navy and Marine Corps TACAIR squadrons worldwide. Directed team that performed post‑analysis of USN-Libyan fighter engagement of 4 JAN 1989. Provided adhoc intelligence support to TOPGUN, MAWTS, STRIKE U and other tactical training commands. Acted as Navy technical review authority for MCM 3‑1, the primary anti‑air threat reference and counter-tactics guide for the armed services. Attained highest possible ratings on performance evaluations and received "Superior Civilian Service" award.

title: Tactical Command and Control Analyst
name: Rick Bolin
description: Helped stand up SPEAR, a new organization comprised of intelligence analysts and naval aviators designed to improve the quality of intelligence reaching operating forces. Analyzed all‑source intelligence and provided threat information to operating forces. Authored or co-authored 7 studies focused on air defense capabilities. Provided 22 briefings at up to 3‑Star level. Headed a USN/USMC working group that helped author MCM 3‑1, the primary air threat reference and counter-tactics guide for the armed services. Represented the Navy on the Joint Service Proforma Coordinating Group, the WSSIC 3rd World C3 Subpanel, the European SAM Tactics Analysis Team, and the JSTPS Enemy Attrition Advisory Group. Contributed to System Threat Assessment Reports produced by Naval Technical Intelligence Center. Headed the Navy delegation to a new foreign intelligence exchange program. Authored portions of National Intelligence Estimates and fleet Operational Tactics Guides. Identified intelligence gaps and generated collection requirements and guidelines for HUMINT, ELINT and SIGINT collection systems. Rated "Outstanding" on all performance evaluations.

title: Senior Staff
name: Rick Bolin
description: Provided engineering and technical support for the US Navy. Reviewed and provided inputs to 67 changes to Trident and SSN‑688 Class electronic system manuals. Work commended by NAVSEA for significantly improving manuals’ accuracy and usefulness. Authored new chapter describing a complex special purpose passive sonar system. Determined the requirements for protecting special hull coatings and side‑mounted sonar arrays on SSN‑688 Class submarines, and authored the applicable operating procedures. Developed technical manuals for the AN/BSY‑1 Combat System on the Seawolf class attack submarine. Performed a complete quality review of the cabling and circuit diagrams for a major AN/BSY‑1 (SUBACS) combat system unit. Assisted with proposal development.

title: Joint Intelligence Research Office (JIRO) Analyst
name: Rick Bolin
description: Served as the JIRO representative on the Technical Support Group, an intelligence advisory cell that evaluated the most sensitive intelligence available for future threat impacts on US systems, and made technical, policy, and funding recommendations for countermeasures to a Navy Flag Officer panel. Analyzed unique information on Soviet tactical C3 and electronic warfare systems, and provided the panel with reports, position papers or briefings on items of significance. Co-authored a major threat assessment titled "Soviet Air Defense Data Links”. Identified major deficiencies in tactical air defense C3 countermeasures, resulting in the formation of a Flag Officer chaired working group tasked to recommend and prioritize programmatic responses. Recommended system capability changes that were adopted for the Battle Group Passive Horizon Extension System (BGPHES), the ALQ‑149/99 jammers, and two classified intelligence systems. Generated a comprehensive intelligence collection requirements and guidance package adopted as high priority tasking for Navy and national collection assets. Represented the Office of Naval Warfare (OP‑95) on the Joint Service Proforma Coordinating Group, a SECDEF mandated Weapon System Commonality Committee, and a Navy Electronic Warfare Working Group. Maintained databases, coordinated meetings, and prepared Flag Officer correspondence.

title: Submarine Weapons and Sensors Analyst
name: Rick Bolin
description: Senior Analyst of Submarine Systems Division. Analyzed all‑source scientific and technical intelligence on foreign submarines. Provided 26 in‑depth briefings on foreign submarine developments to audiences up to Deputy SECDEF level. Contributed regularly to 6 different types of intelligence publications. Authored study presented as a Navy position paper at a multi‑national Maritime Intelligence Conference. Produced the first comprehensive analysis of the Soviet 3rd generation nuclear submarine threat which was published as the lead article in the Naval Scientific and Technical Intelligence Review, and was used by the Director of Naval Intelligence in reporting to Congress. Generated intelligence collection requirements and provided feedback to collectors. Maintained databases on submarine characteristics. Acting Division Head during incumbent's absences, supervising five Naval Officers and two GS‑6. Rated on performance evaluation as the #1 Lieutenant out of 15 at the command.

title: Quality Assurance Officer
name: Rick Bolin
description: Managed the quality assurance (QA) program of a 1000‑man ship that provided repair and logistic services to a squadron of 6 nuclear submarines. Ensured repair standards were met for all non‑nuclear systems. Supervised 26 senior enlisted. Managed training and qualifications program for welders, brazers, and QA inspectors. Reviewed and approved plans and certification testing for over 280 controlled repairs, achieving a zero rate of recurring failures. COMSUBPAC inspection of QA program stated "...the program was excellent...well managed and expertly supervised.” Served as senior officer onboard after working hours, responsible for casualty team training and response, logistic services for submarines (mooring, power, etc.), engineering plant operations, and nuclear weapons security. Completed a Nuclear Regulatory Commission audit of the radiography facility with no significant discrepancies. Received Navy Commendation Medal for "...superb performance...”.

title: Senior Chief Sonar Technician
name: Rick Bolin
description: Lead sonar specialist onboard a Sturgeon‑class fast attack submarine assigned to Submarine Development Squadron Twelve. Supervised 14 sonar technicians in the operation and maintenance of a $40M complex of active and passive sonars and associated digital processing equipment. Developed sonar search plans and made ASW‑related tactical recommendations. Tested and evaluated experimental equipment. Supervised acoustic intelligence (ACINT) collection. Supervised and trained sonar operators in acoustic signature analysis and equipment operation. Trained ship's officers and sonar specialists on Soviet submarine, surface ship, and weapon systems characteristics. Monitored and analyzed ship's radiated noise. Selected for direct commissioning as a US Naval Officer.
